ese quest for transcendence, illuminating a poorly understood tradition that was an important source of Daoist religion and a major social, cultural, and religious phenomenon in its own right.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aTaoistsxBiographyxChina. 0aTaoistszChinavBiography. 7aRELIGION / Taoism (see also PHILOSOPHY / Taoist).2bisacsh  aalchemy.  aancient china.  aarchival work.  aascetics.  abuddhism.  achina.  achinese history.  achinese texts.  aclassicism.  adaoism.  adiscipline.  adivinity.  aeastern philosophy.  agymnastics.  aimmortals.  alost texts.  amedicine.  amedieval china.  ameditation.  amortality.  anonfiction.  aparanormal.  aphilosophy.  areligion.  asexual discipline.  asexual practices.  aspirituality.  asupernatural being.  asupernatural powers.  asupernatural.  ataoism.  ato live as long as heaven and earth.  atraditions of the divine transcendents.  atranscend death.  atranscendents.  atransfiguration.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092760540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520927605423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520927605/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles